  "text": "The Rust borrow checker's MIR analysis chain consists of several key stages orchestrated in the rustc_borrowck compiler crate.\n\n## Entry Point\nThe analysis begins with `mir_borrowck` (compiler/rustc_borrowck/src/lib.rs:117), which is the compiler query entry point. This function creates a `BorrowCheckRootCtxt` and invokes `do_mir_borrowck` (compiler/rustc_borrowck/src/root_cx.rs:242) to coordinate the entire borrow checking process for a function and its nested bodies.\n\n## Region Constraint Collection\n`borrowck_collect_region_constraints` (compiler/rustc_borrowck/src/lib.rs:309) performs the core constraint gathering phase. It:\n1. Calls `nll::replace_regions_in_mir` to replace lexical regions with NLL region variables\n2. Builds the `BorrowSet` (compiler/rustc_borrowck/src/borrow_set.rs) which tracks all borrow locations and manages two-phase borrow state\n3. Runs type checking via `type_check::type_check` to generate constraints\n\n## Two-Phase Borrow Resolution\nTwo-phase borrows are handled in `borrow_set.rs`. The `BorrowData` struct (line 73) stores reservation and activation locations, with `TwoPhaseActivation` enum (line 66) tracking activation state. The `insert_as_pending_if_two_phase` function (line 341) manages pending two-phase borrow activations by tracking temporary assignments and later uses.\n\n## Live Range Calculation\nLiveness analysis is performed through `type_check/liveness/mod.rs::generate` (line 29) which computes which variables are live at which program points. The core algorithm is in `type_check/liveness/trace.rs::trace` (line 40), which performs a reverse depth-first search through the MIR starting from variable uses and drops, computing USE-LIVE and DROP-LIVE sets for regions in variable types.\n\n## Place Conflict Detection\nPlace overlap analysis is implemented in `places_conflict.rs`. The public `places_conflict` function (line 81) checks if two places conflict given a borrow kind and access depth. The core logic in `place_components_conflict` (line 131) iterates through place projections in lockstep, using `place_projection_conflict` to determine if components overlap, disjoin, or have arbitrary overlap (for union types).\n\n## Region Constraint Solving\n`borrowck_check_region_constraints` (compiler/rustc_borrowck/src/lib.rs:389) completes the analysis by calling `nll::compute_regions` (compiler/rustc_borrowck/src/nll.rs:113) to solve region constraints. This creates a `RegionInferenceContext` and performs constraint solving to infer region values.\n\n## Dataflow Analysis\nThe `Borrowck` analysis (compiler/rustc_borrowck/src/dataflow.rs:22) is a composite dataflow analysis combining the `Borrows` flow analysis (line 174) with uninitialized place and ever-initialized place analyses. The `Borrows` analysis tracks which borrows are active at each program point. `OutOfScopePrecomputer` (line 181) computes where borrows go out of scope based on region liveness, enabling efficient out-of-scope tracking during dataflow iteration."
}

